<paragraph blockId="156.[151,1437,1625,1761]" pageId="156" pageNumber="157">
One of the two species described in this genus has been reported from 
<collectingCountry box="[939,1035,1662,1688]" name="Ecuador" pageId="156" pageNumber="157">Ecuador</collectingCountry>
. For the complicated history of species identification in this genus, see the papers by 
<bibRefCitation author="Machado, A. B. M." box="[704,882,1697,1724]" pageId="156" pageNumber="157" pagination="303 - 312" refId="ref195259" refString="Machado, A. B. M. (1954) Elga santosi sp. n. e redescricao de Elga leptostyla Ris, 1911 (Odonata, Libellulidae). Revista Brasileira Biologia, 14 (3), 303 - 312." type="journal article" year="1954">Machado (1954</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Machado, A. B. M." box="[892,952,1698,1724]" pageId="156" pageNumber="157" pagination="153 - 154" refId="ref195347" refString="Machado, A. B. M. (1992) A taxonomic note on Elga Ris, with E. newtonsantosi nom. nov. for E. leptostyla Machado, 1954 (Anisoptera: Libellulidae). Notulae Odonatologicae, 3 (9), 153 - 154." type="journal article" year="1992">1992</bibRefCitation>
). Adults are small, slender dragonflies (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 93" captionStartId="157.[151,250,1371,1396]" captionTargetBox="[303,1285,597,1352]" captionTargetId="figure@157.[303,1285,597,1352]" captionTargetPageId="157" captionText="FIGURE 93. Elga leptostyla ♀, BRAZIL, Río de Janeiro State, Reserva Ecologica de Guapiacu (REGUA), 50m from the stream at the edge of the trail, 15 i 2015; photo B. Guillon" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3335801/files/figure.png" pageId="156" pageNumber="157">Fig. 93</figureCitation>
) that frequent small forested streams.
</paragraph>
